7.10. Proportions with Angle Bisectors www.ck12.org

7.10 Proportions with Angle Bisectors

Here you'll learn how to apply the Angle Bisector Theorem, which states that if a ray bisects an angle of a triangle,

then it divides the opposite side into segments that are proportional to the lengths of the other two sides.

What if you were told that a ray was an angle bisector of a triangle? How would you use this fact to find unknown

values regarding the triangle's side lengths? After completing this Concept, you'll be able to use the Angle Bisector

Theorem to solve such problems.

