James Sousa: Using the Triangle Angle Bisector Theorem to Determine Unknown Values

Guidance

When an angle within a triangle is bisected, the bisector divides the triangle proportionally. This idea is called the

Angle Bisector Theorem.

384

www.ck12.org Chapter 7. Similarity

Angle Bisector Theorem: If a ray bisects an angle of a triangle, then it divides the opposite side into segments that

are proportional to the lengths of the other two sides.

If4BAC ∼=4CAD, then BCCD = ABAD .

Example A

Find x.

The ray is the angle bisector and it splits the opposite side in the same ratio as the other two sides. The proportion is:

9 21

=

x 14

21x = 126

x = 6

Example B

Find the value of x that would make the proportion true.

You can set up this proportion like the previous example.

